Codex Twitch Cohost: Stable Goal and Milestone Plan

Version target for the current refactor line:
- Current working target: 0.4.0
- 1.0.0 is reserved for a stable, predictable conversational character platform

1.0.0 stable definition

The app is 1.0.0 stable only when all of the following are true:

1. Local voice conversation
- Browser speech starts reliably
- Interim transcript appears quickly
- Final transcript commits cleanly
- The bot does not respond to itself
- Ambient noise is ignored instead of being turned into chat
- TTS does not block future turns forever
- Stopping and restarting the mic recovers cleanly

2. Twitch operation
- Twitch connect and disconnect are deterministic
- Bot posting mode is explicit and respected
- Local-only mode works without leaking bot messages into Twitch
- Twitch chat messages, local messages, and bot messages do not cross-contaminate
- Bot mentions, commands, and lurk behavior work predictably

3. Character system
- Character selection feels like choosing a packaged persona
- Each character has:
  - display identity
  - default voice
  - personality tuning
  - avatar
  - memory style
  - scene defaults
- Changing character updates behavior consistently
- Character switching does not corrupt runtime state

4. Memory
- Memory is not just a chat log
- Important facts are extracted and reused
- Corrections override stale facts
- Story continuity is preserved when keep-talking/story mode is enabled
- Memory growth remains bounded and queryable
- Memory retrieval prefers relevant facts over stale noise

5. Avatar
- Embedded avatar is the primary runtime
- Detached avatar is optional, not primary
- Embedded and detached avatar use the same renderer and rig logic
- Mouth and brow rigging persist reliably
- TTS animation does not drift badly or freeze
- The avatar does not require a separate legacy page or duplicated controls
- The renderer has a clean upgrade path from 2D rigging to a WebGPU / wgpu-backed character stage
- Future character rendering can support realistic lighting, mesh deformation, and full 3D character presentation without changing the character data model

6. UI and settings
- One clear design system across the app
- Only active settings panels render
- Controls update live behavior immediately
- No duplicated controls for the same feature
- Desktop and mobile use the same core runtime and layout model

7. Headless backend separation
- The conversational runtime can run without the desktop UI
- The frontend is a controller/client, not the owner of the core runtime
- A CLI or daemon mode can run STT/TTS/chat/memory pipelines without opening a window
- Runtime health and voice checks can be inspected without launching the UI
- The architecture allows future local or remote clients to control the same runtime

8. Stability
- No freeze during normal use
- No unbounded rerender loop
- No zombie speaking state
- No stale mic session that never recovers
- No duplicated config sources fighting each other
- No routine crashes from long sessions, voice churn, or tab changes

9. Diagnostics and automation
- Self-test is meaningful
- Voice runtime can be verified headlessly
- The app has a documented automated validation path
- Every major subsystem has explicit completion criteria

10. External live context and operator awareness
- External live context is backend-owned, not a frontend hack
- Future web search data is source-tagged, time-tagged, and injected safely
- Twitch notifications and stream events can drive operator-facing widgets
- Sampled screen observations can be injected through a dedicated observer subprocess
- Stats, notifications, timeline, and command palette surfaces reflect real backend/runtime signals
- External data never pollutes conversation context without explicit filtering and recency rules
- Screen vision observations are stored as structured summaries, never as uncontrolled raw captions

Milestones

Milestone 0.4.0: architecture and control reliability
- Unified config path for core behavior
- Shared avatar runtime
- Browser speech as primary live STT
- Right-side controls actually mutate backend behavior
- Headless local voice smoke path
- Output normalization fixes for repetitive/opening filler

Done means:
- build passes
- lint passes
- cargo tests pass
- local voice smoke script passes
- no duplicated popup/avatar logic remains in the live path

Milestone 0.5.0: voice stability
- Bot never responds to itself in normal operation
- Browser speech restart and suppression logic is reliable
- Ambient noise rejection is stricter
- TTS state cannot wedge the mic
- Session diagnostics expose timing and restart counters clearly

Done means:
- 3 clean local voice sessions in a row
- no self-reply loop
- no stuck speaking state
- no stuck listening state

Milestone 0.6.0: memory and continuity
- Structured memory wins over raw log spam
- Pinned memory is respected
- Names, titles, and relationship details persist
- Keep-talking mode produces continuation rather than question loops

Done means:
- repeated recall tests pass
- corrections override old facts
- story continuation survives multiple turns

Milestone 0.7.0: Twitch hardening
- Twitch join/leave is deterministic
- Bot local/Twitch posting separation is reliable
- mention replies and commands are reliable
- lurk and cadence settings behave exactly as configured

Done means:
- no unwanted bot posting in local mode
- no accidental reconnect loops
- Twitch-side command behavior matches local diagnostics

Milestone 0.8.0: public voice session foundation
- Public call link flow exists on the shared voice session runtime
- Lightweight public shell
- clear owner/public separation
- no admin-dashboard bloat on the public route

Done means:
- public route works on the shared voice-session architecture
- public shell remains lightweight

Milestone 0.9.0: scene and character maturity
- Solo mode stable
- scene state ready for duo/topic expansion
- preset characters feel like coherent packaged personas
- default voice mapping per character is solid

Done means:
- switching characters does not destabilize voice, memory, or avatar state

Milestone 0.9.5: detached runtime and control plane
- Headless backend mode exists
- UI can act as a controller instead of the only runtime shell
- Runtime health and command/status inspection work without opening the UI
- Voice smoke and service checks run against the backend directly

Done means:
- backend can run without the Tauri window
- the frontend can connect to and control that runtime
- core conversation services survive UI restarts

Milestone 1.0.0: stable release
- all core loops are reliable
- release build behavior matches dev behavior
- diagnostics, docs, and automated verification are trustworthy
- no critical freeze, state corruption, or self-loop issues remain

Automation strategy

What can be tested headlessly now:
- TypeScript/Svelte compile and diagnostics
- production build
- Rust unit tests
- harness tests
- detached `cohostd` backend boot
- detached `cohostd` prompt path
- detached `cohostd` voice smoke through native TTS + local STT
- local fallback STT smoke via Vosk model and helper script

What the architecture must support next:
- the frontend as a thin controller over `cohostd`
- a local control surface for the frontend
- backend child-process health/status commands for STT, TTS, LLM, and Twitch
- the UI as an optional shell rather than the only execution path
- backend-owned external live context ingestion for web search, Twitch events, and screen observation
- sampled screen observer pipeline using structured JSON summaries from multimodal vision models such as qwen2.5vl, gemma3, or llama3.2-vision
- operator widgets driven by backend signals: stats, notifications, timeline, command palette, gauges

What cannot be fully trusted headlessly:
- browser speech recognition quality
- real microphone hardware routing
- speaker echo and room feedback behavior
- live Twitch auth/account flow
- actual user-perceived voice naturalness

Testing rule

A subsystem is not marked complete just because the feature exists.
A subsystem is complete only when:
- failure modes are known
- automated verification exists where possible
- manual validation criteria are explicit where automation is not enough
- recovery behavior is defined

No section is considered done until:
- implementation exists
- regression path is documented
- validation path exists
- known edge cases are mapped
